formatted_address: 495 Geary St, San Francisco, CA 94102, USA
name: Clift San Francisco

reviews.text:
Beautiful hotel, we stayed for a few nights before our wedding (even though we are San Francisco locals) and it was a beautiful experience. The staff were so nice and thoughtful, the suite was large and spacious, an extremely comfortable bed and a dink g area big enough it have the family around for a meals to celebrate together. The staff are very attentive and the hotel feels very secure. 

The Redwood Room was great to gather friends and have drinks, stylish and has a great vibe. 

Overall we can’t recommend this place enough!

The staff was super nice and the hotel is pretty cool. They have a room called The Velvet room or something like that that was a lot of fun. The room itself was just okay. The bed was comfortable but the shower tub situation sucks it's totally old school and for a place of this caliber you would expect to have had a remodel. There are no lights in the closet so it's hard to see your clothes. Not a lot of outlets to plug your stuff in. It's just didn't feel like they were that interested in making sure we were comfortable from a room standpoint once again the staff was amazing and they were all super nice and tell you about the hotel itself

The overall experience at the Clift was great. Staff were friendly, pretty good lobby bar, great location, clean room, etc. There were only 2 things that stopped me from giving this a 5 star. 1) The bathrooms are old and dated. 2) The walls in the bedrooms are very thin. I could here the conversation in the next room. (Side note to the guy in room 427, if your girlfriend moved out and told you she wanted to live alone for a month....chances are she is done with you.....download Tinder)

In conclusion I would stay here again

Awesome classic hotel. The redwood room bar is rad. Stayed in a deluxe suite. Was very large and spacious. Great views of city skyline at night. Rooms are due for an update, especially the bathrooms. Overall had really great time and would definitely stay again.

Beautiful. Huge rooms, nice accommodations. Still under construction on outside of building easy to miss the sign if you're walking. Also has a very aggressive and pushy security staff parked right outside the front doors during night hours.

formatted_address: 140 Ellis St, San Francisco, CA 94102, USA
name: Hotel Fusion

reviews.text: I stayed here with my wife, two adult daughters and future son in law for five days. The hotel has a very nice bar and restaurant and all hotel staff were very friendly. Great location to use public transportation. You can catch a bus or train to all the touristic locations. We read a lot of complaints about bums in San Francisco before choosing this city as our vacation destination and like any major metropolitan area this city does have its fair share of homeless. They are not mean or scary. Just looking for hand outs. I lost about 10 cigarettes, 5 dollars and bought one man two chicken breasts at a corner market. One very nice homeless lady gave me hug for the cigarette. My family and I felt very welcomed and safe at this hotel and in this city.

Very nice hotel close to the BART (train station) in San Francisco. Hotel rooms are small but we'll organised. Security is good. For entertaining inside only card key will work so make sure you lose it. Staff is very helpful and available to help all the time. Overall experience was very good.

Pleasant hotel.  Good buy.  Clean.  Friendly staff.  Jeremy @ concierge desk gave us some excellent recommendations.  The least-expensive, single-bed room is tiny.  But It's a great buy if you don't need a bunch of space.  Great location--very close to multiple kinds of public transportation.  Find best price online, then call the Fusion direct to book.

Perfect for a stay in SF. Rooms are clean and exactly what you need for a trip. The rooms are small, but if you're traveling you will not spend much time in them anyway. Staff is very friendly and willing to get you anything you will need. Central location, although not far from the tenderloin which could be rough so be careful walking weather of the hotel at night. I stay here whenever I'm in town for business.

Nice entrance and perfect location,  but it's downhill from there. The room is dark and depressing and the carpet in the hallway looks like someone dumped motor oil on a white carpet. The most bizarre and disgusting carpet I have ever seen. What were they thinking?

formatted_address: 950 Mason St, San Francisco, CA 94108, USA
name: Fairmont San Francisco

reviews.text: A group of us went to the Tonga room for drinks and dinner. The place is fantastic if you've never been before. Very cool and original. Food and drinks can be expensive so I recommend going during happy hour. If you're there during the band performing they will add 10 per person to the check as well. Well worth it!

Went to the piano bar for some late evening coffee. The hotel is an astoundingly beautiful living museum with hand-carved stone and the historic atmosphere of a grand yesteryear.  However, disorganization reigned  in greeting and seating.  A patron incomprehensibly had her feet up on a chair. Since we were just getting coffee, the bus staff had to do double duty while the waitresses mined the other tables it wasn't crowded nor did it seem like a terribly demanding chore. Not sure, but the beautiful surroundings were filled with a smell of either a dirty carpet or broiled fish. It gave the hallowed surroundings a degraded, atmosphere of lost glory.  Management has a lack of priorities and pride. Unable to comment on the food, but profit seems to take priority customer experience.  A dreadful squandering of a potentially world-class experience.

Besides being an SF institution, its actually a pretty nice hotel too. It hasn't been needlessly modernized in decor and retains its original charm. The service is top notch and I would recommend upgrading. to a high floor. The Top of the Mark is the top floor bar and is worth visiting.

What's not to love.  I felt as though I'd stepped into an old black and white movie.  A romantic Christmas story...
The tree in the lobby was towering with glistening bulbs.  Excited families were gathering around it for their special shot in their best outfits.  The ornate ceilings were twenty plus feet tall.  A ginger bread house made of real gingerbread tiles....All of it was such a memorable experience.  I hope to go back again someday.  I highly recommend!!

Wonderful brunch! Beautiful setting, no wait, and food was super tasty. The man at the omlette station customized my waffle too. The crab omelette was stuffed & the coffee was perfection. Kudos to the great staff.

formatted_address: 2315 Durant Ave, Berkeley, CA 94704, USA
name: Berkeley City Club

reviews.text: We attended a dinner on the second floor. The structure is by Julia Morgan and a lovely example of her architecture. Convenient parking was a block away. Good service. The food was above average.

This is a historic building with beautiful architecture. It has a hotel, clubhouse type functions, and also banquet/event space. I stayed there for a couple nights in the hotel. The room I stayed in was small and didn't have a TV or desk or other contemporary amenities, but it was still a nice place to stay. The room was well maintained and housekeeping did a superb job. There is free continental breakfast, which was minimal but decent quality. They also offer free coffee, Harney teas, and filtered water. There are communal refrigerators on every floor I believe, and a beautiful pool. There is paid parking available. The service was excellent and the employees were all very cordial and helpful.

Beautiful interior, small but adequate rooms.  A few blocks from UC Berkeley.  Ask for a discount if you are an alumni or have a child there.  Restaurant and bar closed Sundays and Mondays but free breakfast served daily.  You have to see the indoor pool!

Such a beautiful facility and the refurbed rooms are nice and now with the afternoon happy hour upstairs (they bought and refurbed the old Larry Blakes on Telegraph Ave bar!) Its a great place for a quiet drink.

This hotel is not for everyone.  But if you appreciate unique, classic architecture; friendly, old school service; and a simple room WITHOUT the idiot box (aka TV), you'll love this place.  Great price and great location mean great value.

name: Graduate Berkeley

reviews.text: Cleanest hotel I've ever stayed at! Rooms are comfy and well organized. Great bed and pillows! The lobby is actually a pleasant place to sit and talk. Super friendly staff. Highly recommended!!

Hotel front desk staff are amazingly helpful. They’re awesome. Unfortunately the bar is currently closed for renovation, the front was eager to apologize and recommend me to their local spots. 

Rooms are a little smaller than what I’m used to in my travels, however the design and decor of the hotel are what really make it. It’s very unique. If I wasn’t used to living in NYC I’d probably find it slightly claustrophobic.

WiFi is a little on the slow side considering the location next to the university, a shabby 4.5 meg down speed, which is almost borderline unacceptable but it’s made up for in other aspects of the hotel, I suppose...

Sorry for the bad camera angles, by small rooms I do mean small.

This was the second hotel in this chain I've stayed at. They are setup to be reminiscent of college dorms. The public space was nice. The breakfast at the lobby bar was much better than I expected. 

The rooms have been updated but are definitely older feeling. Worn wood trim, classic door knobs, steam radiators. The rooms are also fairly small but that may be common to Berkeley, CA. 

The walls are not very well sound proofed. I could hear my neighbor dictating the next great American novel at 6:00am. Also, the bathroom exhaust fan is non-existent. It is just a vent that opens to the neighboring bathroom.
Unique atmosphere. Courteous staff. Comfortable. Clean. Pleasant. (And only a short walk to campus and restaurants.)

If anyone is looking for a great deal on hotels you can see them at HotelRaven.  com Booked a room on there and they had the best rates around...

reviews.text:
First time in SF, went here for dinner last night. It was busy so our group of 4 were understanding of the waitress Brier C being a little slow. But then she became inattentive to us. We found ourselves waiting for her. We ask her to split the checks. Before I could get another word out she was gone. She came back to pick get our cards. She was gone for about 10 minutes. Comes back and rudely tells us she spent 20 minutes trying to split the checks. We complain to the manager. He speaks with her. She comes back and slaps the cards and pen on the table. Brier is one of the worse serves I have ever experienced. 

I ordered the ginger passion fruit soda which was AMAZING. My friends birthday dessert was also really good, sweet and light. 

I do recommend the restaurant but not for a birthday dinner with a group.
Food was superb. Staff was fast on their feet and made sure everything was to our liking. Very nice views and atmosphere. Recommend making a reservation as this place can get packed pretty fast.

Came here for a work party and the food was pretty tasty. I'm vegan and they don't really have vegan options in menu but the chef did what he could to try to ensure I could eat. The servers were friendly and helpful even though we were a very large group with quite a few dietary restrictions. My favorite food options were the plantain chips, potatoes, and the sorbet. Hunny... the mango sorbet was the best thing I've had in a long while!

This place serves great Peruvian food and has a nice outdoor patio to sit by the bay on a sunny day. Most of all though it’s a place to have one of their signature cocktails like a piscina sour during happy hour. And even better if you order it with the plantain chips.

Solid location and food was good. Service was marginal- as the waiter helped a couple parties that arrived after us likely because we were younger-always frustrating. A little expensive, but hey it's waterfront SF.

adr_address: 2442a Webster St, Oakland, CA 94612, USA
formatted_address: 2442a Webster St, Oakland, CA 94612, USA
name: Mua Oakland

reviews.text: The food & cocktails were outstanding. The atmosphere was very unique & enjoyed the music. What I didn't enjoy was the service. We sat at the bar till the rest of our party arrived.....the bartender didn't make eye contact or greet us for over 10min. The hostess was fine. Our server left something to be desired too. (I know we're older & not your typical hip customers but we like good food so treat us like the rest of your tables.)
American funk. Great decor. Love the concept of this place. Cocktails were out of this world. Brussell sprouts were very delicious. Fast service and very very delicious food.

Really cool vibe in Oakland, friendly people and great tasting menu. We had a reservation and still took over a half hour to get seated which was bothersome. Place was absolutely slammed on Friday night, but for good reason. Reasonable prices and good quality bites. Definitely a good spot to share a couple plates and drinks. Loved the beer choices from Iceland and other countries. We'll be back for the environment and good times - food/drink were good but nothing to rave about.

I love this place!  I've come here on different occasions, and the atmosphere is great for dinner with friends or celebrating a birthday. I personally like all the tapas, and the no cheese mac n cheese is delicious!
A funky decor with craft cocktails and an eclectic menu with really tasty food. It’s always full of interesting people and has a very unique vibe. One of my favorite spots in downtown Oakland.

formatted_address: 155 Columbus Ave, San Francisco, CA 94133, USA
name: Comstock Saloon

reviews.text: One of my area favorites! I’d want to not recommend it so highly so I can actually find a seat next time I’m there. Staff has always been very nice to me, the cocktails and wines are high quality, and of-course the live music and vibe are the main attraction. Oh wait! -best Brussels sprouts ever, worth mentioning believe me

I have been going to The Comstock since the time that it opened, since before I even lived in California. it is one of the best bars for cocktails that I have ever experienced. Everything they do is vintage, there are no novelty drinks with funny names, only classics and forgotten classics, and the all-important offering: The Barkeep's Whimsy, where in you can tell the bartender a mood, a favorite ingredient, a kind of drink you feel like you want, and they will come up with something for you. The atmosphere is classic Gilded Age San Francisco, with a little bit of Emperor Norton, but it's never too cute, never too twee. recently, a couple of the original bartenders have moved on, and I was worried that the experience would be lost. To the Comstock's credit those who now run the bar have maintained much of its personality, and all of its quality. it is still one of the best drinks in town, perhaps the best drink in town, if what you look for in a drink is quality. The food menu is a Hidden Gem, few people think of the Comstock as a place to eat, but I have never been disappointed by anything that they offer, and often been pleasantly surprised. Times change, but the Comstock seems to be weathering that critical transition between a beautifully rendered concept, and an established institution.
Cool little joint. We showed up for the live music. Loved it, not too loud and still able to carry a conversation. Loved the french fries!

Great bar, amazing atmosphere, and real bartenders. Great food too but that's an afterthought to their drinks. Great place for anything having to do with whiskey. There was live music the night I went.
Excellent cocktails and a live skiffle band if you get there at the right time. Even the barmen look the part for speakeasy feel.

name: Credo

reviews.text: Excellent place. The food was excellent. The decorations and atmosphere are excellent. The service was excellent. I enjoyed everything I ordered.
Decent happy hour, limited choices. Meatballs were delicious. Quaint bar, good for afternoon mtgs and late lunch. Quiet spot. 4-6pm
Very interesting menu. It's Italian with a little California Fusion added in there. Healthy and delicious very nice presentation. Customer service is great as well!

Came here for a team lunch. Caters to all tastes. The appetizer with Peppers was really good. I had the Crab Sandwich and I loved it. Can book for a large party on Open Table. They have a good drink selection as well. Convenient location near the financial district.

I never take photos of my food, but next time I come back I have to make an exception. Credo was one of the first restaurants my family found in San Francisco upon relocating to the Bay Area, and boy am I glad we found it. This restaurant has all the pieces you need to make an incredible eating experience.

To start, the murals on every wall are both an interesting concept as well as potentially thought provoking. Each credo (how clever), whether or not you agree with it, can have something said for it. In the number of times I’ve been here, I have always managed to find new statements of belief.

The food is incredible, and I’ll be bawling if and when they change their menu, due to the volume of items I’ve fallen in love with. The meals I’ve had and the bites of others’ I’ve shared have been cooked to perfection, with the chefs making a conscious effort to provide bold flavor as well as nourishment. (I’d personally recommend the sedanini for a first-timer entree, and the baked pecorino as a starter.)

Most importantly, the characteristic that can make or break a restaurant - its staff. Credo never ceases to amaze, and while I’m embarrassed to have forgotten to write down the names of some of my past servers, I’d like to personally thank Sabrina for excellent recommendations and prompt, courteous service, as well as Podric, who not only has an arsenal of bartending knowledge at his disposal, but a charming personality that has proved very fun to converse with.

Needless to say I will return many more times!

formatted_address: 330 1st St #1, San Francisco, CA 94105, USA
name: Local Kitchen & Wine Merchant

reviews.text:
I live right around the corner from this place. It's easily missed if you're not paying attention. The food has always been quite stellar but the portion sizes on some of the dishes are pretty small (not the calzone, that's huge).

Great for brunch. Great for dinner. Nice ambiance and you getting he added benefit of working out just from opening the main door :)

Amazing food and atmosphere. Right when you get into the restaurant- the dimly lit atmosphere accented with candles creates the perfect environment for a date night or dinner with friends, just as recommended on Seated. The servers are great and gave us perfect recommendations. I got the black rice with tofu, mushroom pizza, truffle fries and cheesecake. The mushroom pizza melted in my mouth and was the perfect amount of savory. The sauce in the black rice with tofu was sweet and delicious. The black rice with tofu helped balance out the rest of the meal. We topped off the night with a slice of cheesecake to share and it was absolutely perfect. Highly recommend as it was a delicious meal for a great price!

The black rice and tofu "share" dish is actually a good dinner-size portion for one person and absolutely delicious. I think it's gluten free and vegan, too! Decent scotch options at the bar. The design of the space is a nice mix between warm and  modern / interesting. Servers and bar staff seem genuinely friendly and helpful. Overall a good experience and I want to go back.
Had a dinner course meal there and they tasted so bland. Selection of non alcoholic beverages is very limited. The restaurant had good ambience however their Service could be improved.

Good food and drinks at a reasonable price in a nice atmosphere... but from an european view service was slow and inattentive. What's the deal about looking at the table and ask for additional drinks...

formatted_address: 16 Mint Plaza, San Francisco, CA 94103, USA
name: 54 Mint SF

reviews.text:
Service was amazing and the food was super. We arrived pretty early in the evening our food came pretty quickly.

Everything was really nice, simple proper food. Decent selection of wines and I appreciate that the entire menu including wine was not pages and pages. 

Prices are pretty good. Even great for San Francisco.

Good food. Location is kind of hard to find because it's hidden? We don't live in the city, maybe that's another reason but we did use GPS to try to get there, we are Asians so maybe we're just terrible with directions as well? Haha

Bland food. Great service. Feel free to skip unless trying to impress a date.
Honestly, everything was beyond bland and needed salt.
Beautiful plate presentation. Beautiful atmosphere. Awesome staff.
Truly a great experience, just not very good food, especially for the price.

Came for a work outing.  Appetizers were delicious, especially the prosciutto.  Salad was simple and delightful.  Desserts were spectacular.  Red wine forever.

The carbonara was good, a little too much pepper.
Amazing food and cocktails. The smelt appetizer was phenomenal and the pats dishes are adequate portions and very high quality. Awesome place for a date or a birthday.

formatted_address: 690 Mission St, San Francisco, CA 94105, USA
name: The Grove - Yerba Buena

reviews.text: The Grove is a good lunch restaurant. They have long-table seating and individual tables. You order at the counter and take your number to your table and they bring you your food. It was very busy when I went and the food took a little longer than I expected but the Philly cheese steak sandwich was tasty and the side salad was tangy and fresh. They also seem to make some pretty unique sangrias and alcohol infused iced tea beverages. Prices are fairly middle of the road for the Financial District.

This place was some of the best food we ate while in San Fran. From the moment I walked through the door it was spot on. The place is cozy modern yet it’s original making you feel so relaxed to sit in or out for a great meal. Food and atmosphere is very trendy. 
Staff and everyone was great, friendly and on top of what service should be. Now the food OMG AWESOME! I do not need to say much for the food it speaks for its self. I could try everything on the menu and would love it. You know you are at a good place when the manager visits your table to make sure everything is perfect.

Had an early breakfast on a Sunday morning.  There was a line out the door but it moved quickly and we were given a menu to help make decisions while we waited. The staff were very helpful and so friendly.  We ordered the French toast and breakfast burrito.  Definitely some of the best breakfast food we've ever had.  So yummy!  The place has a cool vibe too.  Will definitely go again the next time I'm in San Francisco.

What a find. Spending the weekend from Dallas and wanted a quick but local breakfast. Arrived around 10am to find less than a 10 minute wait. Liked the concept of standing in line to order and then find a seat. Eclectic selection of seating. Food and atmosphere was great. Staff was friendly and helpful. Will be back as soon as possible.

Food is delicious, lines are long but service is fast. Omelettes are pretty small, I was still quite hungry afterward. My friend had the French toast, which had vastly larger portions. All of us really enjoyed the food. Staff is friendly and prompt, and the decor inside looks great. Recommended!

formatted_address: 3907, 325 Columbus Ave, San Francisco, CA 94133, USA
name: The Stinking Rose

reviews.text: Food was delicious!! The staff was wonderful! It was a really great time and, while a bit pricey, was worth every penny. I highly recommend drinking a ginger beer after your meal to ease the tummy. Will definitely go again.  Have the ribeye!

We live in Sacramento and get to San Francisco about 4 times a year. We've seen this restaurant time and again, but have always been put off by the name. However on this Sunday we decided to give it a go. It was a great experience!  The wait staff was very friendly and willing to chat with us. We ordered cocktails to start, and were impressed with the abundant pour. We ordered the baked mussles as an appetizer, split a salad, and shared the black linguine with clams. Although they speak of lots and lots of garlic, the food was very sensibly seasoned. Don't be frightened by the idea of lots of garlic because they don't  overdo it. However if you LIKE garlic you will love this place! Also if you're looking for good Italian food you will love this place.

The food was good but not great. The garlic theme was unique. Unfortunately the rolls were cold and our waiter seemed to want to rush us. The sauce and pasta were good but I have had better at establishments where the price point was a bit less. If you want to see the world's longest garlic braid or if you just love garlic, I would recommend giving this place a try.

If you don't like garlic you have no business being here. It's a garlic restaurant. Fresh chopped garlic pesto on the table that alone will leave you smelly like garlic for a week. The garlic boat thing gives you a roasted garlic the spreads like butter and goes well on bread. The brie cheese was pretty good. Not a huge fan of their caeser dressing but it was still good. We had the pasta and gnocchi and it was great. It was our first visit. Service is good. Made reservations on open table and we're sat right away.

I used to live Davis for many years and went to this place roughly 2-3 times a year. Ever since l moved to SoCal, I visit S.F. at least once a year for a conference. My kids are now in college but come with me, and this is the place they want to go. It doesn't matter what to order since they are all good. Very friendly servers. Always pleasant experience.

formatted_address: 22 Hawthorne St, San Francisco, CA 94105, USA
name: Benu

reviews.text: Was there not for the regular menu but a La Paulee event. It was meant to be the most impressive wine paired dinner. Chef had to change the menu for red wine pairing. I would say it's a fail. There were risks taken but dishes were not memorable. And some dishes I wouldn't want to have again. The service is what's most disappointing. The program flow were disrupted with sometimes 20min gaps. Bad execution.

Asian inspired Michelin star restaurant.  Many flavors were familiar to Korean palette.  Most dishes were inventive and familiar at the same time.  There were a few dishes I didn't love, the faux shark fin, chicken wing stuffed with abalone were a couple.  The 1000 year old egg, hairy prawn (that's what I call it), lobster dumplings, and beef dishes were excellent.  The desserts we're not too sweet, simple and cleansing.  The service was outstanding.  I'm not sure if I'll go back though.

The delicacies in the beginning were my favorite - exquisite and delicious. Didn’t like the “main” dishes, eg the chicken leg stuffed with abalone, and really did not like the dessert (winter melon with frozen meringue and a berry sorbet. The service was excellent, striking a perfect balance of being attentive and not hovering. The one weird thing is that they remove the dishes before I finish eating that particular course. This happened twice! I have 3 bites left and they just started clearing the my plates! I thought it was rude and it made me feel rushed.

Oh my goodness, Benu is to die for. From the attentive, polite, friendly waitstaff to the perfect wine pairing selections, everything surrounding Cory Lee's food is perfect. But the food itself goes beyond that. I can't even describe it with words. The 1,000 Year Egg was especially amazing, as was the winter melon with chrysanthemum flower dessert.
Impeccable execution by chef Corey Lee and team!  Our New year's Eve dinner was delicious. What a perfect way to end an awesome year and to welcome an exciting new year! Thanks for having us!

formatted_address: 4001 Judah St, San Francisco, CA 94122, USA

reviews.text: Your typical trendy brunch spot. Chose this place because our friends from out of town needed vegan options and we heard good things about this place. I'm not a vegan so I can't say if this was a good option, my friend ordered some mushroom soup which for me didn't sound appetizing or filling. The grilled cheese was really good, we added bacon which made it that much better. I ordered the chicken sandwich, the chicken was a little on the dry side for me but overall I liked it.

This is a true 5 star spot for either breakfast or dinner. Get there early for breakfast so you can get a table. A half an hour before opening should suffice. Put your name on their list and just hang out until they open. The interior is beautiful and has a great design with wood accents all around. Don't be timid to sit outside, even if it is a bit chilly since they have outdoor heaters above each table.
As for food, my go to is always the Eggs in Jail. Their bread is out of this world. Coffee is Four Barrel or formerly known as. Solid place. No complaints.

Really lovely place in a lovely spot - great for a post walk/run/cycle in the park or along the beach. We waited only about 30 mins at the height of Saturday brunch. Food and drinks were delicious and although I liked the menu it was a little short. Service was lovely. It’s on the pricey side at $80 for 2 people (2 mains, 1 desert, and 4 drinks)

Great brunch option in the Outer Sunset. The salmon, egg sandwich were our mains, and we split the thick cut toast.  (see pics)  Really great.  Put your name on the list and grab some coffee at trouble coffee company while you wait, and check out the cute stores along the way. Great way to spend your morning in SF

I've been coming to Outerlands since they first opened, and this place has never disappointed me. Always something new and fresh to try on the menu. A little tip, come late night for dinner on weeknights after 9:30 to avoid the crowds.
